{"title_page": "Altrincham F.C.", "text_new": "{{short description|English association football club}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname      = Altrincham\n| image         = Altrincham CrestNew.png\n| alt           = Altrincham crest\n| fullname      = Altrincham Football Club\n| nickname      = The Robins, Alty\n| ground        = [[Moss Lane]], [[Altrincham]]\n| capacity      = 6,085 (1,154 seated)<ref name=NLCD>Mike Williams & Tony Williams (2012) ''Non-League Club Directory 2013'', p165 {{ISBN|978-1-869833-77-0}}</ref>\n| founded       = 1891\n| chairman      = Grahame Rowley\n| manager       = Phil Parkinson\n| league        = {{English football updater|Altrinch}}\n| season        = {{English football updater|Altrinch2}}\n| position      = {{English football updater|Altrinch3}}\n| current       =\n| website       = www.altrinchamfc.com\n<!-- Home kit -->\n| pattern_la1 = _whiteshoulders\n| pattern_b1  = _red_stripes_red_sholders\n| pattern_ra1 = _whiteshoulders\n| pattern_sh1 = _whitesides\n| pattern_so1 = _band_black\n| leftarm1    = FF0000\n| body1       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1   = FF0000\n| shorts1     = 000000\n| socks1      = FF0000\n<!-- Away kit -->\n| pattern_la2 = _whiteborder\n| pattern_b2  = _whiteredleftsash\n| pattern_ra2 = _whiteborder\n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 =\n| leftarm2    = D3D3D3\t\n| body2       = D3D3D3\t\n| rightarm2   = D3D3D3\t\n| shorts2     = D3D3D3\t\n| socks2      = D3D3D3\t\n}}[[File:Exeter City match.JPG|right|thumb|[[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] vs Altrincham, in a [[National League (division)|Conference National]] fixture played on 19 August 2006]]\n\n'''Altrincham Football Club''' is a semi-professional [[association football|football]] club based in [[Altrincham]], [[Greater Manchester]], England. Founded in 1891 and nicknamed \"the Robins\", they are currently members of {{English football updater 2|{{English football updater|Altrinch}}}} and play at [[Moss Lane]].\n\n==History==\n{{see also|List of Altrincham F.C. seasons}}\nAltrincham was established by a [[Sunday school]] around 1891 as Rigby Memorial Club.<ref name=H1>[http://www.lusaweb.co.uk/history.htm Altrincham F.C., a Brief History] Altrincham F.C.</ref> They soon merged with another local team, Grapplers, to form Broadheath Football Club,<ref name=H1/> and were founder members of the [[Manchester Football League|Manchester League]] in 1893.<ref name=FCHD>{{fchd|id=ALTRINCH|name=Altrincham}}</ref> Their first match in the league on 16 September 1893 saw them lose 7\u20130 to Hulme, and they went on to lose 14 of the remaining league matches as they finished bottom of the table.<ref>[http://www.altrinchamfc.co.uk/altyhtol.htm A to Z of Altrincham Football Club] Altrincham F.C.</ref>\n\nAfter playing at various grounds in [[Broadheath, Greater Manchester|Broadheath]], [[Timperley]] and Altrincham, the club moved to Pollitt's Field in 1903, at which point they changed their name to Altrincham.<ref name=H1/> They won the Cheshire Amateur Cup in their first season under the new name, and went on to win both the Manchester League and the [[Cheshire Senior Cup]] the following season.<ref name=H1/> They won the Manchester League again in [[1906\u201307 in English football|1906\u201307]], and moved to their current [[Moss Lane]] ground in 1910.<ref name=H1/> \n\nIn 1911 the club joined Division Two of the [[Lancashire Combination]].<ref name=FCHD/> They finished as runners-up in their first season in the division, only missing out on the title on [[Goal difference|goal average]] and earning promotion to Division One.<ref name=FCHD/> They remained in Division One until [[World War I]]. When football resumed in 1919, the club were founder members of the [[Cheshire County League]], where they remained until [[World War II]], the highlights being finishing as runners-up in [[1934\u201335 in English football|1934\u201335]] and [[1935\u201336 in English football|1935\u201336]] and a League Cup win in [[1932\u201333 in English football|1932\u201333]].<ref name=H1/><ref name=FCHD/> In [[1934\u201335 FA Cup|1934\u201335]] they reached the first round of the [[FA Cup]] for the first time, losing 1\u20130 at [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]].<ref name=FCHD/>\n\nAfter missing out the [[1945\u201346 in English football|1945\u201346]] season, they rejoined the Cheshire County League in 1946, achieving little success until the 1960s, when Altrincham director Noel White hired Freddie Pye as manager. A key turning point in the history of the club is often cited as the signing of [[Jackie Swindells]] in 1965, who in his first full season (1965\u201366) scored 82 goals.<ref>[http://www.altrinchamfc.co.uk/legend21.htm Altrincham Football Club Legends Section Eighteen Profiles 52\u201354] Altrincham F.C.</ref> helping Altrincham to the first of back-to-back Cheshire County League titles, scoring over 120 goals in the league in both seasons. After finishing as runners-up in [[1967\u201368 in English football|1967\u201368]], they were founder members of the [[Northern Premier League]] in 1968.<ref name=FCHD/>\n\nThey reached the semi-finals of the [[FA Trophy]] in [[1976\u201377 in English football|1976\u201377]], losing 2\u20131 to [[Scarborough F.C.|Scarborough]] in a second replay;<ref name=FCHD/> the season also saw them apply for election to the [[English Football League|Football League]] for the first time, but they received only 12 votes compared to the 27 received by the elected [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]].<ref name=NLM/> The following season they went one better in the FA Trophy, reaching the [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]] final, where they beat [[Leatherhead F.C.|Leatherhead]] 3\u20131. In [[1978\u201379 Northern Premier League|1978\u201379]] they finished as runners-up in the Northern Premier League and applied for election to the Football League again. Although they finished as the top [[Non-League football|non-League]] club in the ballot, they received only 13 votes to the 37 received by [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]], the lowest-placed Football League club.<ref name=NLM>[http://www.nonleaguematters.co.uk/forum/gforum.cgi?do=post_attachment;postatt_id=3506; A history of admission to the Football League] Non-League Matters</ref> Instead, Altrincham became founder members of the [[National League (English football)|Alliance Premier League]], the top level of non-League football, the winner of which would be the sole non-League nomination for future Football League election ballots.\n\nThe league's [[1979\u201380 Alliance Premier League|inaugural season]] saw Altrincham crowned champions.<ref name=FCHD/> In the subsequent elections to the Football League, the club missing out by a single vote, receiving 25 to [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]]'s 26; this was considered especially unfortunate as the club had been promised the votes of [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] and [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]], but the Grimsby representative was prevented from voting by being in the wrong part of the meeting room, whilst the Luton representative arrived too late after a mix-up over the start time.<ref>Dave Twydell (2001) ''Denied F.C.: The Football League election struggles'', Yore Publications, p27</ref> \n\nAltrincham retained the APL title the [[1980\u201381 Alliance Premier League|following season]], but again failed in the Football League elections, this time only receiving 15 votes to the 41 received by Halifax, who were again the lowest ranked Football League club.<ref name=NLM/> The next two seasons saw the club finish in mid-table, together with another FA Trophy final appearance in [[1981\u201382 FA Cup|1981\u201382]], this time losing 1\u20130 to [[Enfield F.C.|Enfield]]. This was followed by four consecutive top-five finishes between 1984 and 1987 and a second FA Trophy win in 1985, beating [[Runcorn F.C. Halton|Runcorn]] 1\u20130 in the final. The [[1985\u201386 FA Cup|1985\u201386 season]] saw them record one of the biggest FA Cup giant-killings of all time when they defeated top division [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] 2\u20131 at Birmingham's [[St Andrew's (stadium)|St Andrew's]].<ref>{{cite news |title=FA Cup: John Motson's 10 FA Cup third-round shocks |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30466552 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=2 January 2015 |accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50139021 |title=FA Cup first round: Guide to the 31 non-league teams taking part |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe club then returned to mid-table with occasional successful seasons, finishing third in [[1990\u201391 Football Conference|1990\u201391]] (by which time the league had become the Football Conference) and fourth in [[1994\u201395 Football Conference|1994\u201395]].<ref name=FCHD/> After finishing bottom of the Conference in [[1996\u201397 Football Conference|1996\u201397]] the club were relegated to the Premier Division of the [[Northern Premier League]]. An eighth-place finish in [[1997\u201398 Northern Premier League|1997\u201398]] saw them return to the Conference two seasons later as [[1998\u201399 Northern Premier League|Premier Division champions]].<ref name=FCHD/> However, they lasted only a [[1999\u20132000 Football Conference|single season]] in the Conference as they finished second-from-bottom and were relegated back to the Northern Premier League. \n\nA twelfth-place finish in [[2003\u201304 Northern Premier League|2003\u201304]] saw them qualify for the newly formed [[National League North|Conference North]]. They finished fifth in the new division in its [[2004\u201305 Football Conference|first season]], qualifying for the promotion play-offs. After defeating [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Borough]] 4\u20132 on penalties following a 1\u20131 draw and then [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]] 3\u20132, they were promoted to the Conference National division with a 2\u20131 win over [[Eastbourne Borough F.C.|Eastbourne Borough]] in the North/South final played at the [[Bet365 Stadium|Britannia Stadium]].<ref name=FCHD/>\n\nIn [[2005\u201306 Football Conference|2005\u201306]] Altrincham finished bottom of the Conference National after receiving an 18-point deduction when they were found to have fielded an ineligible player, [[James Robinson (footballer, born 1982)|James Robinson]], for 15 matches, during which he scored six goals and Altrincham won 18 points. However, they were reprieved from relegation after [[Canvey Island F.C.|Canvey Island]] resigned from the league and Scarborough were demoted.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scarborough relegation confirmed |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/5044276.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 June 2006 |accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref> The [[2006\u201307 Football Conference|following season]] they again finished in the relegation zone, but were reprieved after [[Boston United F.C.|Boston United]] were demoted.<ref>{{cite news |title=Heathcote joy at Robins reprieve |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/altrincham/6740873.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 June 2007 |accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref> A third successive relegation reprieve occurred in [[2007\u201308 Football Conference|2007\u201308]] when Halifax were [[Liquidation|liquidated]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Leagues agreed for 2008/09 season |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/7402814.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter mid-table finishes in [[2008\u201309 Football Conference|2008\u201309]] and [[2009\u201310 Football Conference|2009\u201310]] and [[Ricky Ponting]] becoming a shareholder of the club in 2009,<ref>{{cite news |title=Ponting handed Altrincham shares |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/altrincham/8181662.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 August 2009 |accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref> Altrincham were relegated to the Conference North at the end of the [[2010\u201311 Football Conference|2010\u201311 season]]. In [[2012\u201313 Football Conference|2012\u201313]] a fourth-place finish saw them qualify for the promotion play-offs, in which they lost 4\u20132 on aggregate to [[Brackley Town F.C.|Brackley Town]]. However, after finishing fourth the [[2013\u201314 Football Conference|following season]], they beat [[Hednesford Town F.C.|Hednesford Town]] 4\u20133 on aggregate in the semi-finals and then defeated [[Guiseley A.F.C.|Guiseley]] 2\u20131 in the final to earn promotion back to the Conference National.<ref name=FCHD/> In [[2015\u201316 National League|2015\u201316]] the club finished in the relegation zone and were relegated to the renamed National League North.<ref name=FCHD/> The [[2016\u201317 National League|following season]] they finished bottom of the National League North, leading to a second successive relegation to the Premier Division of the Northern Premier League.  However, the [[2017\u201318 Northern Premier League|2017\u201318 season]] saw the club win the Northern Premier League title, earning promotion back to the National League North.\n\nIn [[2018\u201319 National League#National League North|2018\u201319]] Altrincham finished fifth in the National League North, earning a place in the play-offs; in the quarter finals, they drew 2\u20132 with [[Blyth Spartans A.F.C.|Blyth Spartans]] before winning 7\u20136 in a penalty shootout, setting up a semi-final tie with [[Chorley F.C.|Chorley]], which they lost 3\u20131 on penalties after a 1\u20131 draw.\n\n===FA Cup giant-killers===\nAltrincham have a history of [[Upset (competition)|giant-killing]] in the [[FA Cup]], holding the record of knocking out more Football League sides than any other club that has spent its entire history playing in [[Non-League football|non-League]].<ref>{{cite news |title=How to kill an FA Cup giant |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29945185 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 November 2017 |accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref> To date the club has recorded seventeen victories against Football League clubs:\n#1921\u201322: Tranmere Rovers defeated 4\u20132 in the fourth qualifying round<ref name=H1/>\n#1965\u201366: Rochdale defeated 3\u20131 in the second round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1973\u201374: [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool]] defeated 2\u20131 in the first round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1974\u201375: [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] defeated 3\u20131 in a first round replay<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1979\u201380: [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] defeated 3\u20130 in the first round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1979\u201380: [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] defeated 2\u20130 in the second round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1980\u201381: Scunthorpe United defeated 1\u20130 in a second round replay<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1981\u201382: [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] defeated 3\u20130 in a first round replay<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1981\u201382: [[York City F.C.|York City]] defeated 4\u20133 in a second round replay<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1982\u201383: Rochdale defeated 2\u20131 in the first round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1984\u201385: [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] defeated 1\u20130 in the first round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1985\u201386: Blackpool defeated 2\u20131 in the second round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1985\u201386: [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] defeated 2\u20131 in the third round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1988\u201389: [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] defeated 3\u20132 in the first round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1992\u201393: [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] defeated 2\u20130 in a second round replay<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1994\u201395: [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] defeated 1\u20130 in the second round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#2015\u201316: [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] defeated 1\u20130 in the first round<ref name=FCHD/>\n\nThe club reached the third round of the FA Cup in four consecutive seasons, and between the years 1978 to 1982, boasted a more impressive record in the competition than any club playing in the old third and fourth divisions (levels 3-4).. \n\n==Current squad==\n<!-- PLEASE READ THIS BEFORE UPDATING\n\nIf you change the squad list, please amend the update date below.\n\nDo not add any players not listed in the first team page on the Altrincham website used to source this list.\n-->\n{{updated|6 December 2019}}<ref>[https://www.altrinchamfc.com/teams/first-team] Altrincham F.C.</ref>\n{{fs start}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=GK |name=[[Steven Drench]]}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=GK |name=[[Tony Thompson (footballer)|Tony Thompson]]}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=GK |name=Joel Torrance}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=Shaun Densmore}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=Toby Mullarkey}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=Connor Hampson}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=Tom Hannigan}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=WAL |pos=DF |name=James Jones}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=Andrew White}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=Josh Hancock}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Max Harrop]]}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=Jake Moult}}\n{{fs mid}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Simon Richman]]}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=Sean Williams}}\n{{Fs player |no=  |nat=IRE |pos=MF |name=[[Craig Mahon]]}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=Luke Wall}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=WAL |pos=MF |name=[[Dan Mooney]]}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=Jordan Hulme}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=Tom Peers}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=Lewis Walters}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=Curtis Miller}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=[[Elliott Durrell]]}}\n{{fs end}}\n\n==Honours==\n*'''[[National League (English football)|National League]]'''\n**Champions 1979\u201380, 1980\u201381\n**[[Conference League Cup|Bob Lord Trophy]] winners 1980\u201381\n*'''[[Northern Premier League]]'''\n**Premier Division champions 1998\u201399, 2017\u201318\n**Challenge Cup winners 1969\u201370, 1997\u201398\n**Challenge Shield winners 1979\u201380, 1998\u201399\n*'''[[Manchester Football League|Manchester League]]'''\n**Champions 1904\u201305, 1906\u201307\n*'''[[Cheshire County League]]'''\n**Champions 1965\u201366, 1966\u201367\n*'''[[FA Trophy]]'''\n**Winners: 1977\u201378, 1985\u201386\n*'''[[Cheshire Senior Cup]]'''\n**Winners 1904\u201305, 1933\u201334, 1966\u201367, 1981\u201382, 1998\u201399, 2004\u201305, 2008\u201309\n**League Cup winners 1932\u201333, 1950\u201351, 1963\u201364\n*'''Cheshire Amateur Cup'''\n**Winners 1903\u201304\n\n==Records==\n*Best [[FA Cup]] performance: Fourth round, 1985\u201386\n*Record attendance: 10,275, Altrincham Boys vs [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland Boys]], 28 February 1925<ref name=R>[http://www.altrinchamfc.co.uk/club.htm Club Information] Altrincham F.C.</ref>\n*Record transfer fee paid: \u00a315,000 to [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] for [[Keith Russell (footballer)|Keith Russell]], 1998<ref name=R/>\n*Record transfer fee received: \u00a350,000 from [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] for [[Kevin Ellison (footballer)|Kevin Ellison]], 2001<ref name=R/>\n*Record victory: 14\u20132 vs Sale Holmfield, Cheshire Amateur Cup, 5 December 1903<ref name=R/>\n*Record defeat: 13\u20131 vs Stretford, 4 November 1893<ref name=R/>\n*Most appearances: Stuart Coburn, 689 (1997\u20132002, 2003\u20132016)<ref>\"Stuart Coburn\", ''The Non-League Football Paper'', 25 June 2017</ref>\n*Most goals: [[Jackie Swindells]], 252 (1965\u20131971)<ref name=NLCD/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[:Category:Altrincham F.C. players|Altrincham F.C. players]]\n*[[:Category:Altrincham F.C. managers|Altrincham F.C. managers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|www.altrinchamfc.com}}\n\n{{National League (English football)}}\n{{Football in Greater Manchester}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Altrincham F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:1891 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1891]]\n[[Category:Cheshire County League]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Trafford]]\n[[Category:Lancashire Combination]]\n[[Category:Manchester Football League]]\n[[Category:National League (English football)]]\n[[Category:Northern Premier League clubs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English association football club}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname      = Altrincham\n| image         = Altrincham CrestNew.png\n| alt           = Altrincham crest\n| fullname      = Altrincham Football Club\n| nickname      = The Robins, Alty\n| ground        = [[Moss Lane]], [[Altrincham]]\n| capacity      = 6,085 (1,154 seated)<ref name=NLCD>Mike Williams & Tony Williams (2012) ''Non-League Club Directory 2013'', p165 {{ISBN|978-1-869833-77-0}}</ref>\n| founded       = 1891\n| chairman      = Grahame Rowley\n| manager       = Phil Parkinson\n| league        = {{English football updater|Altrinch}}\n| season        = {{English football updater|Altrinch2}}\n| position      = {{English football updater|Altrinch3}}\n| current       =\n| website       = www.altrinchamfc.com\n<!-- Home kit -->\n| pattern_la1 = _whiteshoulders\n| pattern_b1  = _red_stripes_red_sholders\n| pattern_ra1 = _whiteshoulders\n| pattern_sh1 = _whitesides\n| pattern_so1 = _band_black\n| leftarm1    = FF0000\n| body1       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1   = FF0000\n| shorts1     = 000000\n| socks1      = FF0000\n<!-- Away kit -->\n| pattern_la2 = _whiteborder\n| pattern_b2  = _whiteredleftsash\n| pattern_ra2 = _whiteborder\n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 =\n| leftarm2    = D3D3D3\t\n| body2       = D3D3D3\t\n| rightarm2   = D3D3D3\t\n| shorts2     = D3D3D3\t\n| socks2      = D3D3D3\t\n}}[[File:Exeter City match.JPG|right|thumb|[[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] vs Altrincham, in a [[National League (division)|Conference National]] fixture played on 19 August 2006]]\n\n'''Altrincham Football Club''' is a semi-professional [[association football|football]] club based in [[Altrincham]], [[Greater Manchester]], England. Founded in 1891 and nicknamed \"the Robins\", they are currently members of {{English football updater 2|{{English football updater|Altrinch}}}} and play at [[Moss Lane]].\n\n==History==\n{{see also|List of Altrincham F.C. seasons}}\nAltrincham was established by a [[Sunday school]] around 1891 as Rigby Memorial Club.<ref name=H1>[http://www.lusaweb.co.uk/history.htm Altrincham F.C., a Brief History] Altrincham F.C.</ref> They soon merged with another local team, Grapplers, to form Broadheath Football Club,<ref name=H1/> and were founder members of the [[Manchester Football League|Manchester League]] in 1893.<ref name=FCHD>{{fchd|id=ALTRINCH|name=Altrincham}}</ref> Their first match in the league on 16 September 1893 saw them lose 7\u20130 to Hulme, and they went on to lose 14 of the remaining league matches as they finished bottom of the table.<ref>[http://www.altrinchamfc.co.uk/altyhtol.htm A to Z of Altrincham Football Club] Altrincham F.C.</ref>\n\nAfter playing at various grounds in [[Broadheath, Greater Manchester|Broadheath]], [[Timperley]] and Altrincham, the club moved to Pollitt's Field in 1903, at which point they changed their name to Altrincham.<ref name=H1/> They won the Cheshire Amateur Cup in their first season under the new name, and went on to win both the Manchester League and the [[Cheshire Senior Cup]] the following season.<ref name=H1/> They won the Manchester League again in [[1906\u201307 in English football|1906\u201307]], and moved to their current [[Moss Lane]] ground in 1910.<ref name=H1/> \n\nIn 1911 the club joined Division Two of the [[Lancashire Combination]].<ref name=FCHD/> They finished as runners-up in their first season in the division, only missing out on the title on [[Goal difference|goal average]] and earning promotion to Division One.<ref name=FCHD/> They remained in Division One until [[World War I]]. When football resumed in 1919, the club were founder members of the [[Cheshire County League]], where they remained until [[World War II]], the highlights being finishing as runners-up in [[1934\u201335 in English football|1934\u201335]] and [[1935\u201336 in English football|1935\u201336]] and a League Cup win in [[1932\u201333 in English football|1932\u201333]].<ref name=H1/><ref name=FCHD/> In [[1934\u201335 FA Cup|1934\u201335]] they reached the first round of the [[FA Cup]] for the first time, losing 1\u20130 at [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]].<ref name=FCHD/>\n\nAfter missing out the [[1945\u201346 in English football|1945\u201346]] season, they rejoined the Cheshire County League in 1946, achieving little success until the 1960s, when Altrincham director Noel White hired Freddie Pye as manager. A key turning point in the history of the club is often cited as the signing of [[Jackie Swindells]] in 1965, who in his first full season (1965\u201366) scored 82 goals.<ref>[http://www.altrinchamfc.co.uk/legend21.htm Altrincham Football Club Legends Section Eighteen Profiles 52\u201354] Altrincham F.C.</ref> helping Altrincham to the first of back-to-back Cheshire County League titles, scoring over 120 goals in the league in both seasons. After finishing as runners-up in [[1967\u201368 in English football|1967\u201368]], they were founder members of the [[Northern Premier League]] in 1968.<ref name=FCHD/>\n\nThey reached the semi-finals of the [[FA Trophy]] in [[1976\u201377 in English football|1976\u201377]], losing 2\u20131 to [[Scarborough F.C.|Scarborough]] in a second replay;<ref name=FCHD/> the season also saw them apply for election to the [[English Football League|Football League]] for the first time, but they received only 12 votes compared to the 27 received by the elected [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]].<ref name=NLM/> The following season they went one better in the FA Trophy, reaching the [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]] final, where they beat [[Leatherhead F.C.|Leatherhead]] 3\u20131. In [[1978\u201379 Northern Premier League|1978\u201379]] they finished as runners-up in the Northern Premier League and applied for election to the Football League again. Although they finished as the top [[Non-League football|non-League]] club in the ballot, they received only 13 votes to the 37 received by [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]], the lowest-placed Football League club.<ref name=NLM>[http://www.nonleaguematters.co.uk/forum/gforum.cgi?do=post_attachment;postatt_id=3506; A history of admission to the Football League] Non-League Matters</ref> Instead, Altrincham became founder members of the [[National League (English football)|Alliance Premier League]], the top level of non-League football, the winner of which would be the sole non-League nomination for future Football League election ballots.\n\nThe league's [[1979\u201380 Alliance Premier League|inaugural season]] saw Altrincham crowned champions.<ref name=FCHD/> In the subsequent elections to the Football League, the club missing out by a single vote, receiving 25 to [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]]'s 26; this was considered especially unfortunate as the club had been promised the votes of [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] and [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]], but the Grimsby representative was prevented from voting by being in the wrong part of the meeting room, whilst the Luton representative arrived too late after a mix-up over the start time.<ref>Dave Twydell (2001) ''Denied F.C.: The Football League election struggles'', Yore Publications, p27</ref> \n\nAltrincham retained the APL title the [[1980\u201381 Alliance Premier League|following season]], but again failed in the Football League elections, this time only receiving 15 votes to the 41 received by Halifax, who were again the lowest ranked Football League club.<ref name=NLM/> The next two seasons saw the club finish in mid-table, together with another FA Trophy final appearance in [[1981\u201382 FA Cup|1981\u201382]], this time losing 1\u20130 to [[Enfield F.C.|Enfield]]. This was followed by four consecutive top-five finishes between 1984 and 1987 and a second FA Trophy win in 1985, beating [[Runcorn F.C. Halton|Runcorn]] 1\u20130 in the final. The [[1985\u201386 FA Cup|1985\u201386 season]] saw them record one of the biggest FA Cup giant-killings of all time when they defeated top division [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] 2\u20131 at Birmingham's [[St Andrew's (stadium)|St Andrew's]].<ref>{{cite news |title=FA Cup: John Motson's 10 FA Cup third-round shocks |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30466552 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=2 January 2015 |accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50139021 |title=FA Cup first round: Guide to the 31 non-league teams taking part |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe club then returned to mid-table with occasional successful seasons, finishing third in [[1990\u201391 Football Conference|1990\u201391]] (by which time the league had become the Football Conference) and fourth in [[1994\u201395 Football Conference|1994\u201395]].<ref name=FCHD/> After finishing bottom of the Conference in [[1996\u201397 Football Conference|1996\u201397]] the club were relegated to the Premier Division of the [[Northern Premier League]]. An eighth-place finish in [[1997\u201398 Northern Premier League|1997\u201398]] saw them return to the Conference two seasons later as [[1998\u201399 Northern Premier League|Premier Division champions]].<ref name=FCHD/> However, they lasted only a [[1999\u20132000 Football Conference|single season]] in the Conference as they finished second-from-bottom and were relegated back to the Northern Premier League. \n\nA twelfth-place finish in [[2003\u201304 Northern Premier League|2003\u201304]] saw them qualify for the newly formed [[National League North|Conference North]]. They finished fifth in the new division in its [[2004\u201305 Football Conference|first season]], qualifying for the promotion play-offs. After defeating [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Borough]] 4\u20132 on penalties following a 1\u20131 draw and then [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]] 3\u20132, they were promoted to the Conference National division with a 2\u20131 win over [[Eastbourne Borough F.C.|Eastbourne Borough]] in the North/South final played at the [[Bet365 Stadium|Britannia Stadium]].<ref name=FCHD/>\n\nIn [[2005\u201306 Football Conference|2005\u201306]] Altrincham finished bottom of the Conference National after receiving an 18-point deduction when they were found to have fielded an ineligible player, [[James Robinson (footballer, born 1982)|James Robinson]], for 15 matches, during which he scored six goals and Altrincham won 18 points. However, they were reprieved from relegation after [[Canvey Island F.C.|Canvey Island]] resigned from the league and Scarborough were demoted.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scarborough relegation confirmed |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/5044276.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 June 2006 |accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref> The [[2006\u201307 Football Conference|following season]] they again finished in the relegation zone, but were reprieved after [[Boston United F.C.|Boston United]] were demoted.<ref>{{cite news |title=Heathcote joy at Robins reprieve |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/altrincham/6740873.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 June 2007 |accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref> A third successive relegation reprieve occurred in [[2007\u201308 Football Conference|2007\u201308]] when Halifax were [[Liquidation|liquidated]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Leagues agreed for 2008/09 season |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/7402814.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter mid-table finishes in [[2008\u201309 Football Conference|2008\u201309]] and [[2009\u201310 Football Conference|2009\u201310]] and [[Ricky Ponting]] becoming a shareholder of the club in 2009,<ref>{{cite news |title=Ponting handed Altrincham shares |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/altrincham/8181662.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 August 2009 |accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref> Altrincham were relegated to the Conference North at the end of the [[2010\u201311 Football Conference|2010\u201311 season]]. In [[2012\u201313 Football Conference|2012\u201313]] a fourth-place finish saw them qualify for the promotion play-offs, in which they lost 4\u20132 on aggregate to [[Brackley Town F.C.|Brackley Town]]. However, after finishing fourth the [[2013\u201314 Football Conference|following season]], they beat [[Hednesford Town F.C.|Hednesford Town]] 4\u20133 on aggregate in the semi-finals and then defeated [[Guiseley A.F.C.|Guiseley]] 2\u20131 in the final to earn promotion back to the Conference National.<ref name=FCHD/> In [[2015\u201316 National League|2015\u201316]] the club finished in the relegation zone and were relegated to the renamed National League North.<ref name=FCHD/> The [[2016\u201317 National League|following season]] they finished bottom of the National League North, leading to a second successive relegation to the Premier Division of the Northern Premier League.  However, the [[2017\u201318 Northern Premier League|2017\u201318 season]] saw the club win the Northern Premier League title, earning promotion back to the National League North.\n\nIn [[2018\u201319 National League#National League North|2018\u201319]] Altrincham finished fifth in the National League North, earning a place in the play-offs; in the quarter finals, they drew 2\u20132 with [[Blyth Spartans A.F.C.|Blyth Spartans]] before winning 7\u20136 in a penalty shootout, setting up a semi-final tie with [[Chorley F.C.|Chorley]], which they lost 3\u20131 on penalties after a 1\u20131 draw.\n\n===FA Cup giant-killers===\nAltrincham have a history of [[Upset (competition)|giant-killing]] in the [[FA Cup]], holding the record of knocking out more Football League sides than any other club that has spent its entire history playing in [[Non-League football|non-League]].<ref>{{cite news |title=How to kill an FA Cup giant |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29945185 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 November 2017 |accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref> To date the club has recorded seventeen victories against Football League clubs:\n#1921\u201322: Tranmere Rovers defeated 4\u20132 in the fourth qualifying round<ref name=H1/>\n#1965\u201366: Rochdale defeated 3\u20131 in the second round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1973\u201374: [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool]] defeated 2\u20131 in the first round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1974\u201375: [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] defeated 3\u20131 in a first round replay<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1979\u201380: [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] defeated 3\u20130 in the first round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1979\u201380: [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] defeated 2\u20130 in the second round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1980\u201381: Scunthorpe United defeated 1\u20130 in a second round replay<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1981\u201382: [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] defeated 3\u20130 in a first round replay<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1981\u201382: [[York City F.C.|York City]] defeated 4\u20133 in a second round replay<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1982\u201383: Rochdale defeated 2\u20131 in the first round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1984\u201385: [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] defeated 1\u20130 in the first round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1985\u201386: Blackpool defeated 2\u20131 in the second round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1985\u201386: [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] defeated 2\u20131 in the third round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1988\u201389: [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] defeated 3\u20132 in the first round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1992\u201393: [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] defeated 2\u20130 in a second round replay<ref name=FCHD/>\n#1994\u201395: [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] defeated 1\u20130 in the second round<ref name=FCHD/>\n#2015\u201316: [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] defeated 1\u20130 in the first round<ref name=FCHD/>\n\nThe club reached the third round of the FA Cup in four consecutive seasons, and between the seasons 1978 to 1982, boasted a more impressive record in the competition than any club playing in the old third and fourth divisions (levels 3-4).. \n\n==Current squad==\n<!-- PLEASE READ THIS BEFORE UPDATING\n\nIf you change the squad list, please amend the update date below.\n\nDo not add any players not listed in the first team page on the Altrincham website used to source this list.\n-->\n{{updated|6 December 2019}}<ref>[https://www.altrinchamfc.com/teams/first-team] Altrincham F.C.</ref>\n{{fs start}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=GK |name=[[Steven Drench]]}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=GK |name=[[Tony Thompson (footballer)|Tony Thompson]]}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=GK |name=Joel Torrance}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=Shaun Densmore}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=Toby Mullarkey}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=Connor Hampson}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=Tom Hannigan}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=WAL |pos=DF |name=James Jones}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=Andrew White}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=Josh Hancock}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Max Harrop]]}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=Jake Moult}}\n{{fs mid}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Simon Richman]]}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=Sean Williams}}\n{{Fs player |no=  |nat=IRE |pos=MF |name=[[Craig Mahon]]}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=Luke Wall}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=WAL |pos=MF |name=[[Dan Mooney]]}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=Jordan Hulme}}\n{{fs player |no=  |nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=Tom Peers}}\n{{fs player |